<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA73C5DFF6BBA4FFCB38023" blockId="1.[151,805,1050,1077]" box="[151,805,1050,1077]" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<heading id="D0BD6E35FFA73C5DFF6BBA4FFCB38023" bold="true" box="[151,805,1050,1077]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="239" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA73C5DFF6BBA4FFCB38023" bold="true" box="[151,805,1050,1077]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
Key to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA73C5DFEE3BA4EFE288022" box="[287,446,1050,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Teuchothrips</taxonomicName>
species from 
<collectingCountry id="F35D99C9FFA73C5DFD94BA4FFCB38023" box="[616,805,1050,1077]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3508AD2FFA73C5DFF6BBA34FA0A81C2" pageId="1" pageNumber="239" type="key">
<keyStep id="30BEC1FCFFA73C5DFF6BBA34FA0A80DA" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA73C5DFF6BBA34FA0A8085" blockId="1.[151,1437,1119,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<keyLead id="30BB7A6CFFA73C5DFF6BBA34FA0A8085" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">1. Maxillary stylets widely separated, about 50% of head width apart, retracted into head no more than one third of distance to posterior margin of eyes................................................................................ 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA73C5DFF6BBACFFA0A80DA" blockId="1.[151,1437,1119,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<keyLead id="30BB7A6CFFA73C5DFF6BBACFFA0A80DA" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">- Maxillary stylets close together, no more than 25% of head width apart and sometimes crossing over each other, retracted to posterior margin of eyes................................................................................ 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30BEC1FCFFA73C5DFF6BBA81FA0A8155" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA73C5DFF6BBA81FA0A8110" blockId="1.[151,1437,1119,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<keyLead id="30BB7A6CFFA73C5DFF6BBA81FA0A8110" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
2. Fore tibia of both sexes with small tubercle at inner apex; postocular and pronotal major setae pointed; antennal segment III yellow, IV–V bicolored; fore wing with 13–16 duplicated cilia.......................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA73C5DFAC4BAA6FA0A8110" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1975" box="[1336,1436,1266,1287]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cleistanthi">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA73C5DFAC4BAA6FA0A8110" box="[1336,1436,1266,1287]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">cleistanthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA73C5DFF6BBB44FA0A8155" blockId="1.[151,1437,1119,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<keyLead id="30BB7A6CFFA73C5DFF6BBB44FA0A8155" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
- Fore tibia of both sexes without apical tubercle; postocular and pronotal major setae weakly capitate; antennal segments III–V yellow; fore wing with 10–12 duplicated cilia.......................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA73C5DFAABBB79FA0A8155" baseAuthorityName="Bournier" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[1367,1436,1325,1346]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kraussi">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA73C5DFAABBB79FA0A8155" box="[1367,1436,1325,1346]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">kraussi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30BEC1FCFFA73C5DFF6BBB1EFA0A81C2" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA73C5DFF6BBB1EFA0A816A" blockId="1.[151,1437,1119,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<keyLead id="30BB7A6CFFA73C5DFF6BBB1EFA0A816A" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
3. Occipital ridge of head simple and transverse (
<figureCitation id="1371C5DCFFA73C5DFD63BB1EFD4F8177" box="[671,729,1354,1376]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,181,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[153,1434,181,1746]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Heads of paratypes of Teuchothrips species. (1) cleistanthi; (2) kraussi; (3) ornatus; (4) noumeaensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6405146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6405146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); head extensively reticulate; pronotal anteromarginal setae small, 0.25 as long as antennal segment III, 0.16 as long as epimeral setae............................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA73C5DFAAFBB3CFA0A816A" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1993" box="[1363,1436,1384,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatus">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA73C5DFAAFBB3CFA0A816A" box="[1363,1436,1384,1405]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">ornatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5D959FFA73C5DFF6BBBD1FA0A81C2" blockId="1.[151,1437,1119,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
<keyLead id="30BB7A6CFFA73C5DFF6BBBD1FA0A81C2" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">
-. Occipital ridge of head with curved sculptured area medially (
<figureCitation id="1371C5DCFFA73C5DFCB8BBD1FCE9818C" box="[836,895,1413,1435]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,181,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[153,1434,181,1746]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Heads of paratypes of Teuchothrips species. (1) cleistanthi; (2) kraussi; (3) ornatus; (4) noumeaensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6405146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6405146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); head with transverse lines, reticulate posterolaterally; pronotal anteromarginal setae well developed, 0.5 as long as antennal segment III, 0.5 as long as epimeral setae..................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C4AA2DAFFA73C5DFADCBB94FA0A81C2" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1993" box="[1312,1436,1472,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="noumeaensis">
<emphasis id="B93E054BFFA73C5DFADCBB94FA0A81C2" box="[1312,1436,1472,1493]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="239">noumeaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
